<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In the long run, according to the quantity theory of money, what is the primary determinant of inflation?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Changes in velocity of money</option>
            <option letter="b">Changes in real GDP</option>
            <option letter="c">Changes in money supply growth</option>
            <option letter="d">Changes in interest rates</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The quantity theory of money suggests that in the long run, with velocity (V) and real GDP (Y) relatively stable, the growth rate of the money supply (M) is the primary determinant of inflation (P). This is why sustained inflation is often described as a monetary phenomenon.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
